<div id="review_1736681064" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1736681064" />
    <a title="Armin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58913296-armin"><img alt="Armin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1584015407p2/58913296.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1736681064?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Armin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Armin" href="/user/show/58913296-armin">Armin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58913296-armin?shelf=plays">plays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/58913296-armin?shelf=french">french</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1736681064" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3090343212496694904">So I figured ir&apos;s a recurrent post-renaissance tradition that Astyanax (Hector and Andromaque&apos;s son) survives the Trojan War through a hoax his mom conducts on Ulysses...<br/>Anyway Racine&apos;s Andromaque has a very different setting with Euripides&apos;s: Peleus and Menelaus are not around and Molossus does not exist, Hermione and Andromaque interact very little and very politely (in comparison to the hectic exchange they have in the Greek version with Andromaque&apos;s witty lines), Andromaque&apos;s efforts are foc</span>
  <span id="freeText3090343212496694904" style="display:none">So I figured ir's a recurrent post-renaissance tradition that Astyanax (Hector and Andromaque's son) survives the Trojan War through a hoax his mom conducts on Ulysses...<br />Anyway Racine's Andromaque has a very different setting with Euripides's: Peleus and Menelaus are not around and Molossus does not exist, Hermione and Andromaque interact very little and very politely (in comparison to the hectic exchange they have in the Greek version with Andromaque's witty lines), Andromaque's efforts are focused on saving Hector's son. Hermione and Orestes have different types of encounters too.<br />I personally loved the Greek version better, I find it more demanding and more challenging. Racine's version is sometimes sensual but Euripides has peoduced a more melancholic text where although there is less ruin in it, there's more at stake! I definitely suggest reading them back to back though!</span>
  <a data-text-id="3090343212496694904" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1736681064">
