    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_230779877" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/230779877" />
    <a title="Justin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5856040-justin"><img alt="Justin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593125872p2/5856040.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/230779877?book_show_action=true">Nov 03, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Justin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Justin" href="/user/show/5856040-justin">Justin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer230779877" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2742640361242000871">&quot;Hell hath no fury like a woman scorned&quot;. My first introduction to Racine through the 1960 blank verse translation by Muir, this strong tragedy from one of &quot;The Big Three&quot; of post-Jacobian French drama (along with Molière and Corneille) is an adept look into the lives, loves, hatred and psyche of the heirs of the Iliad. Though not nearly as compelling, poetic, or rich as those of the Elizabethan theatre (read: Shakespeare), the pathos is solid; a fully cathartic play.</span>
  <span id="freeText2742640361242000871" style="display:none">"Hell hath no fury like a woman scorned". My first introduction to Racine through the 1960 blank verse translation by Muir, this strong tragedy from one of "The Big Three" of post-Jacobian French drama (along with Molière and Corneille) is an adept look into the lives, loves, hatred and psyche of the heirs of the Iliad. Though not nearly as compelling, poetic, or rich as those of the Elizabethan theatre (read: Shakespeare), the pathos is solid; a fully cathartic play.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2742640361242000871" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


