    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2244984473" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2244984473" />
    <a title="Greg" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6922605-greg"><img alt="Greg" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1320867217p2/6922605.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2244984473?book_show_action=true">Jan 05, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Greg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Greg" href="/user/show/6922605-greg">Greg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780156075107" href="/book/show/665267.Andromache">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6922605-greg?shelf=drama">drama</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2244984473" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15354999594935803529">In the introduction to the Penguin edition to this play, John Cairncross states that “One can hardly hope to do justice to Racine unless one is bilingual, or practically so. For he yields his secrets to the Anglo-Saxon reader far less readily than, say, Dante or Goethe, owing in part to the weakness of the tonic accent in French, and above all to the difference of the conventions governing his poetry and ours.” In Andromache, fate is anonymous and vindictive. It is an ever-present trait of each </span>
  <span id="freeText15354999594935803529" style="display:none">In the introduction to the Penguin edition to this play, John Cairncross states that “One can hardly hope to do justice to Racine unless one is bilingual, or practically so. For he yields his secrets to the Anglo-Saxon reader far less readily than, say, Dante or Goethe, owing in part to the weakness of the tonic accent in French, and above all to the difference of the conventions governing his poetry and ours.” In Andromache, fate is anonymous and vindictive. It is an ever-present trait of each person. Fate seems to guide the action between absolute power, the passion of the characters, and death. The play is spare, and the tragedy powerful. Also in the introduction, Cairncross states, “the pattern…as often been reduced to a mathematical formula. A loves B who loves C who loves D, and in each case the love is unrequited. But if D accepts C’s addresses, B lends a kindlier ear to A, who then, to please B, murders C.” While he goes on to provide much more depth to this formula, I would agree it is correct. <br /><br />“Do not expect me then to answer for<br />A heart so little master of itself.<br />He may, sir, in this frenzied turmoil wed<br />The one he hates and spurn the one he loves.”<br /><br />This is the central conflict of the play.<br /><br />In the end, I find this play difficult to review. It is a wonderfully classic play by one of the most influential playwrights of all time. It is also quite foreign to modern readers, and it is difficult to relate to these characters and the tragedy. Maybe the best review is to quote from the play itself: “I have loved him too much not to hate” <br /><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/6922605-greg?page=1&amp;shelf=read" rel="nofollow noopener">See my other reviews here!</a><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15354999594935803529" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

