<span id="freeTextContainer13254283094179546041">A few life-lessons from this play.<br/><br/>One: If a prisoner of war won&apos;t date you (despite all those wonderful death threats you keep making), maybe you&apos;re just not being convincing enough. Try again.<br/><br/>Two: Everything is always about Orestes. Man decides to marry his fiance? It MUST be because Man doesn&apos;t want ORESTES to date her. That&apos;s it. EVERYTHING IS ALWAYS ABOUT MEEEEE.<br/><br/>Three: Pyrrhus is definitely over Andromache. &quot;Yeah. I mean, I have other things to do than flirt with (/threaten) her all day. Lot</span>
  <span id="freeText13254283094179546041" style="display:none">A few life-lessons from this play.<br /><br />One: If a prisoner of war won't date you (despite all those wonderful death threats you keep making), maybe you're just not being convincing enough. Try again.<br /><br />Two: Everything is always about Orestes. Man decides to marry his fiance? It MUST be because Man doesn't want ORESTES to date her. That's it. EVERYTHING IS ALWAYS ABOUT MEEEEE.<br /><br />Three: Pyrrhus is definitely over Andromache. "Yeah. I mean, I have other things to do than flirt with (/threaten) her all day. Lots of things. I'm a total catch. Who does she think she is? Pff. Who cares about her? I don't care. I definitely don't care. Even if she is super gorgeous. [shouts loudly] JUST GONNA GO KILL HER SON NOW. AS SOON AS I COUNT TO TEN. UNLESS SHE MAYBE THINKS I'M GORGEOUS NOW. GONNA START COUNTING NOW. ONE... TWO... is she looking yet?"<br /><br />Four: Each character gets a confidant/bestie. Everyone asks for their advice (and then decides they definitely won't follow it).<br /><br />But all's well that ends well because Andromache gets to be queen at the end and lives happily ever after, the end. And Orestes gets chased by furies. I think. How does this keep happening to him?</span>
  <a data-text-id="13254283094179546041" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

