<div id="review_3161384576" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3161384576" />
    <a title="Charlie Whiteside" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/96258317-charlie-whiteside"><img alt="Charlie Whiteside" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1555710822p2/96258317.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3161384576?book_show_action=true">Jan 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Charlie Whiteside" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Charlie Whiteside" href="/user/show/96258317-charlie-whiteside">Charlie Whiteside</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3161384576" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6934558852572615849">I&apos;ve decided to start writing mini-reviews to just record my thoughts on what I read more than from a critical standpoint.<br/><br/>This was surprisingly readable for me (in English translation), and having never read a Greek play I didn&apos;t have much hope for plot complexities. It was however surprisingly convoluted and I found myself liking it despite not usually enjoying many older texts I read for my course. Racine&apos;s interpretation is blunt and uses simple yet formal language, but most likely less so th</span>
  <span id="freeText6934558852572615849" style="display:none">I've decided to start writing mini-reviews to just record my thoughts on what I read more than from a critical standpoint.<br /><br />This was surprisingly readable for me (in English translation), and having never read a Greek play I didn't have much hope for plot complexities. It was however surprisingly convoluted and I found myself liking it despite not usually enjoying many older texts I read for my course. Racine's interpretation is blunt and uses simple yet formal language, but most likely less so than the play did in the original forms.<br /><br />The characters definitely aren't realistic in the slightest and are defined by their actions, but that was both deliberate and a product of its' age as a text. I also wouldn't particularly be interested in seeing a stage performance either, as it's very monologue-heavy piece without much actual acting - Racine and other French playwrights of the time also indended this, so it can't be criticised directly based on this choice.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6934558852572615849" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


